<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-115-396  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 115 396.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>High Technology Business  April 1989 v9 n4 p28(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tooth tech: the new dentistry.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Biesada, Alexandra M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Modern dentistry is turning to such high-tech tools as computerimaging systems, surgical lasers, fiber optics, and CAD-CAMsystems.andP;  Professional Services Institute, a Sacramento, CA,software firm, offers the $6,300 Nu View 1000 computer imagingsystem.andP;  Dentists can use such systems to preview the cosmeticresult of dental work such as orthodonture or tooth caps.andP;  ThePre-View Dental Imaging System from McGhan InstruMed Corp,Carpinteria, CA, for $12,400, is a similar system modified from aversion marketed to plastic surgeons.andP;  Dental applications ofCAD-CAM, initiated in France, are being developed by HennsonInternational, Los Angeles.andP;  CAD-CAM systems allow design andproduction of prosthesi without a physical model.andP;  Systems can beaccessed via mailed floppy disk or dial-up modem.andP;  Lasertechnology will be in common use in dental surgery by the end ofthe 1990s.andP;  While dentists are slow to adopt new technology,proponents say it will be necessary to stay competitive in thefuture, when cavities will account for less of the dentist'sbusiness.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Professional Services Institute (products)McGhan InstruMed Corp (products)Hennson International (product development).andO;Product:   Professional Services Institute Nu View 1000 (Computer system)(usage)McGan InstruMed Pre-View Dental Imaging System (Computer system)(usage).andO;Topic:     CAD-CAMImaging TechnologyFiber OpticsDentistryApplicationsFuture TechnologiesLasersProducts.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   The endosseous fixtures market. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>